# CDK Infrastructure Standards

## Stack Naming
- All stacks use `{deployment_namespace}-{stack_purpose}` (e.g., `portal-stevens-dev-data`)
- Resource names derived from config context — never hardcoded strings
- No hardcoded AWS account IDs, regions, or ARNs anywhere in CDK code

## Construct Preferences
- Prefer L2/L3 constructs over L1 (`Cfn*`) unless an L2 does not exist
- Wrap repeated patterns in custom L3 constructs (see `constructs/lambda_function.py`, `constructs/monitored_table.py`)
- Keep constructs single-responsibility: one construct, one resource group

## Resource Configuration
- All resource names derived from `namespace` and config dict, never hardcoded
- Use `config` dict from context for client-specific values (table names, bucket names, feature flags)
- Environment-tier logic lives in config files (`config/example.json`), not in stack code

## IAM
- Least-privilege: scope policies to `{namespace}-*` resource ARNs
- No wildcard (`*`) resource ARNs in production policies
- Use `grant_*` methods on L2 constructs instead of hand-rolling IAM statements
- Service roles scoped to the stack's own resources only

## Alarms
- Each stack owns its own alarms (distributed alarm model)
- Alarm names follow `{namespace}-{resource}-{metric}` pattern
- Use `TreatMissingData.NOT_BREACHING` for low-traffic resources

## Testing
- CDK assertions for resource existence (`has_resource_properties`)
- Assert resource property values match config-derived names
- Test that IAM policies are scoped (no `Resource: *`)
- Snapshot tests for stack template stability
